(3/3) Finally, I am fully supporting the border supplemental introduced today - $4.5B in emergency $$ to address the humanitarian crisis, including legal aid, food, water, medical services, support services for unaccompanied children, alternatives to detention, + refugee services

(2/3) The bill also provides funding to get more individuals out of cells and into communities with their loved ones as they go through immigration proceedings. And of course, it blocks any and all funding for the WALL.

(1/3) This year’s spending bill phases out family detention by end of FY 2019 – I actually introduced an amendment to do this last year, but was voted down by my colleagues on the other side of the aisle.
